What are our goals?

  • Divide observed signal by stellar model (black body to start with)
  • Identify better stellar model spectra for better handling of $H$ lines
  • Compare night-to-night, year-to-year spectral response to gauge the variability
  • Troubleshoot artifacts in the data- cosmic rays, spurious signals

We'll start with the first task.

In [7]: 
def blackbody_lam(lam, T):
    """ Blackbody as a function of wavelength (um) and temperature (K).

    returns units of erg/s/cm^2/cm/Ste # convert to metres
    """
    from scipy.constants import h,k,c
    lam = 1e-6 * lam # convert to metres
    return 2*h*c**2 / (lam**5 * (np.exp(h*c / (lam*k*T)) - 1))

Cool! At the zoom-out-to-10,000-feet-view, the spectral response looks fairly constant, and different effects from different spectral types are evident. It's also clear that, gee-whiz, it'd be really nice to find a template spectrum of these stars so we can divide out the broad $H$ lines, rather than just linearly extrapolating over them. The intrinsic spectral features are just too numerous and broad to really get away with linear extrapolation, or Black Body curves.

We want a model spectrum with the same or higher resolution! Well... I found one:

http://www.nhn.ou.edu/~alexg/publications/Moehler_2014_SPIE_9080_91490L.pdf

http://cdsarc.u-strasbg.fr/viz-bin/Cat?J/A%2bA/568/A9

Here we have to be a little cautious about the interpolation. I tried to run the interpolation on the full dataset and my laptop had a meltdown- i.e, it ran out of RAM. Here is a blog post about how to do this right: http://www.astrobetter.com/python-tip-re-sampling-spectra-with-pysynphot/ This sent me on a quest to see if pysynphot exists in astropy yet. It doesn't, but I found a stand-alone version. Importing it throws a lot of warnings, but I think it's OK to ignore them.

In [13]: 
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

from pysynphot import observation
from pysynphot import spectrum
 
def rebin_spec(wave, specin, wavnew):
    spec = spectrum.ArraySourceSpectrum(wave=wave, flux=specin)
    f = np.ones(len(wave))
    filt = spectrum.ArraySpectralElement(wave, f, waveunits='angstrom')
    obs = observation.Observation(spec, filt, binset=wavnew, force='taper')
 
    return obs.binflux

Let's do a pixel-by-pixel estimate of the mean and variance of the spectrum. We can fit with some long-tailed distributions to be robust against outliers (cosmic rays, systematic errors). My experience on this is limited, so I'll try a few distributions and compare the results and stick with the one I like the best.

In [18]:

n_spec = 627
specs = numpy.concatenate((ltt3218_set,ltt7987_set), axis=1)
spec_d = np.zeros((n_spec, 2))
spec_t = np.zeros((n_spec, 2))
spec_c = np.zeros((n_spec, 2))

print shape(spec_d[:,1])

for i in range(n_spec):
    spec_d[i,:] = [np.mean(specs[i, :]), np.std(specs[i, :])]
    t_shape, t_loc, t_scale = stats.t.fit(specs[i, :])
    spec_t[i,:] = [t_loc, t_scale]

We should perform some surgery in the vicinity of $H\alpha$. First idea is to smooth the spectrum, then replace the errant data points with the smoothed spectrum. Here's our chance for either Nadaraya-Watson or median smoothing. In the process of doing this we are going to make new estimators, so let's define the Spectral Response $R_\lambda $ as $$R_\lambda = f_{\lambda}/\hat{f}_{\lambda}$$ Then, let's just focus on the wavelength range surrounding $H\alpha$

So, yes, Airmass does matter enough to have to deal with it. So what we want to do is apply the smoothing of the $H\alpha$ blip to every spectrum, and not just the average one. Before we get too far with this, I want to reduce and refine the other telluric stars HR5517 and HR6939. Both in terms of getting their 1D spectra reduced (need to ID the right to-slit that it was sent to), and to then divide them by a model of an A0V star.

Let's explain what it is that we're plotting above. It is the observed telluric spectrum, $f_\lambda$, divided by the blackbody Planck spectrum $B_\lambda$ assuming an effective temperature $T$ listed in the file "tell_stds.csv", divided by the assumed average response function $R_\lambda$. Let's define it as $\eta $ :

$$ \eta = \frac{f_{\lambda}}{B_{\lambda}(T)} \frac{1}{R_\lambda}$$

One key idea is that we can construct an estimator for the intrinsic spectrum of HR5517 and HR6930 in the following way. We'll combine the highest quality spectra of HR5517 and HR6930 from the nights for which we have near-contemporaneous similar-airmass spectra of LTT3218 and LTT7987. Then we will smooth over any minor features of known telluric origin. Let's drop the $\lambda$ subscripts and instead mark the observed telluric spectral flux density with $f_o$, our estimator for the "True" spectrum flux with $f_T$.

$$\hat{f}_{True} = \hat{\eta}B(T)$$

This is only sort of cheating, and sort of bad. There are several issues making this strategy sub-optimal. Chiefly, we are adding twice the noise than we have to (noise from eta-hat and noise from our telluric observation). There are also the concerns of "do we have the black body effective temperature right?" and "how good is our estimate $\hat{\eta}$, and do telluric features creep into it?" My intuition says that all these issues matter at such a small level that we don't care, and can just move on. The Right Thing to Do would be to match exactly what $\tt{xTellCorr}$ from $\tt{SpeXtool}$ does-- namely, go out and find a model spectrum of the same spectral type, then convolve the spectral lines of the model to the match the doppler broadened observed lines. There's also a B-V correction to do. All of that would require hacking SpeXtool, which although noble, would take longer to do than what I'm doing now since it would require debugging someone else's code.

It's important to emphasize that this strategy only works in comparison to response functions derived with near-contemporaneous similar-airmass observations. You can tell by looking at the figure above that observations from other nights and years look very different. That's exactly why we wish to construct the estimator $\hat{f}_{True}$ so that we can apply it to those other ones. Whew. OK here we go.

My guess for why the NC spectra look awful is that the spectral mapping was busted. Stupid. Well, let's just focus on the good data for the moment. We cleaned all of the $H\alpha$ regions as we did before... so that's done. I also cleaned the instances of two obvious cosmic rays. I did this by hand, but oh-well. I saved the spectral response (for the good ones, i.e. NONE from nc200_75) to ascii tables. But still the question remains of what to do with the NC200_75 response functions. Cosmos handled these so badly that they are demolished. Here are my strategies for fixing them:

  • Fix the spectra one at a time by making a custom .SMF file with only 2 or 3 slits that are nearby each other. This way the map-spectra won't get so thrown off by spurious signals. The 2 or 3 slits would be chosen for their clean appearance in the arc frames.
  • Just copy the map files from functional spectral maps. The best way to do this is probably to run map-spectra and then spectral map either once or maybe not at all if the subsequent steps can handle that. I noticed that the arc frame residuals actually got worse when I re-ran the spectral-map function the second time. This bad behavior can be interpreted as the mask has overlapping spectra and is getting pulled away by adjacent erroneous lines.
  • Lastly, we could really drill down and overplot the fits to the lines to see where and when the fits are missing, but this will take a lot of user-intervention and visual analysis and writing code, etc. So this last procedure is a worst case scenario.

<<Pretty sure second order light leaked into the telluric spectra (aka UGHHHHH.)>>

Well, let's check. We'll use an A0V spectrum (instead of a white dwarf), so that the comparison is more accurate. Then we'll overlay the second order spectrum with the first order spectrum. Naturaly we do not know the relatve efficiency of the orders, so we will artifically scale the spectrum by-eye. I assume 10% for now.

from astropy.io import fits

vega_fn = BAADE + '/data/analysis/vega_k93.fits'

model_full = vega[:,1]/np.median(vega[:,1])

sec_ord_rat = 0.1
net_flx = model_scl + sec_ord_flux*sec_ord_rat

model_norm = model_scl/np.median(model_scl)

Hmm... the synthetic spectrum doesn't match in the positions, but the number and shape of spurious lines is comparable. The positions should match, based purely on diffraction grating theory. It almost looks like everything should be shifted over a little bit... wait a minute... Ta-da! If you change the wavelength multiplier to 1.94 instead of 2.0 (for second order), you get nearly perfect position agreement. I chock up the 3% difference to subtleties of vacuum vs. air wavelengths, and the detailed optical distortions of IMACS and higher order chromatic effects of the grisms, filters, etc. So it's settled. So wow! This stinks! The path forward is to reduce the spectrum from the southeas slit mask that has an observation of a telluric through both filters. That will give us some constraint on the amplitude of the effect, and maybe we can still calibrate the spectral response in some convoluted way.

The first step forward is just to make a ratio a ratio array we can work with.

There are a few things to notice here. First, the spectra of the same stars through two different filters look different. The spectra are noisier than I would have expected, and there are strange artifacts notable in the Spectroscopic2 filter. The overlapping lines are just barely evident in the spectrum of HR6930 through the Spectroscopic2 filter, which is hard to understand given the veiling seen in the cluster of lines between 8500-9000 $\unicode{x212B}$. The strange appearance of the spectrum might be due to the fact that we exposed the spectrum in a non-standard way. Specifically, we had to defocus the telescope to avoid saturation of the telluric spectrum.
